Ch. 18 - Linear Regression Models - Problem 18.1 Crime and Punishment

The data in linearRegression_crimePunishment.csv contains the murder rate per capita and the rate of automobile crimes per 100,000 individuals (both on the log scale) in the ten US States that have changed their legislation on capital punishment since 1960 (in all cases the states abolished capital punishment). We also include a dummy variable (law) that is 1 if the state allows capital punishment in that year, and 0 otherwise. The crime data is from http://www.disastercenter.com.

cp_data <- readr::read_csv(here::here("STAN", "data", 
                                      "linearRegression_crimePunishment.csv")) %>% 
  select(-X1) %>% janitor::clean_names() %>% 
  mutate(state_name = factor(state_name),
         state = as.integer(state),
         law = as.integer(law))
## Warning: Missing column names filled in: 'X1' [1]

Problem 18.1.1. Graph the data and comment on any trends.

library(ggplot2)

p <- ggplot(data = cp_data, aes(x = year)) + 
  geom_line(aes(y = murder), color = "red") + 
  geom_line(aes(y = car), color = "green") + 
  geom_line(aes(y = law), color = "blue") +
  facet_grid(rows = vars(state_name))

p

There seems to be some association between the murder rate and auto crimes. In all cases it is difficult to visually discern an impact of the change in legislation.

Problem 18.1.2.

A simple model for murder rates is of the form:

\[ murder_{i,t} N(\alpha + \beta \times penalty_{i,t} + \gamma \times car_{i,t}, \sigma) \] where we assume that the effect of having the death penalty is given by , which is assumed to be the same across all states. We include \(car_{i,t}\) a measure of crimes on automobiles, as an independent variable to proxy for the contemporaneous underlying level of crime. Estimate this model and hence determine whether the death penalty acts as a deterrent to murder.

library(rstan)
## Loading required package: StanHeaders
## rstan (Version 2.21.2, GitRev: 2e1f913d3ca3)
## For execution on a local, multicore CPU with excess RAM we recommend calling
## options(mc.cores = parallel::detectCores()).
## To avoid recompilation of unchanged Stan programs, we recommend calling
## rstan_options(auto_write = TRUE)
## Do not specify '-march=native' in 'LOCAL_CPPFLAGS' or a Makevars file
## 
## Attaching package: 'rstan'
## The following object is masked from 'package:tidyr':
## 
##     extract
options(mc.cores = parallel:: detectCores())
rstan_options(auto_write = TRUE)

data_list <- list(N       = nrow(cp_data),
                  murder  = cp_data$murder,
                  penalty = cp_data$law,
                  car     = cp_data$car)

set.seed = 1

fit <- stan(here::here("STAN", "problem_18_1_linear_regression", "c_p.stan"), 
            data = data_list, 
            iter = 1000, 
            chains = 4, 
            warmup = 500)
print(fit, c("alpha", "beta_car", "beta_penalty", "sigma", "lp__"))

Where we see that we estimate that the imposition of the death penalty on average raises the murder rate by on average 24%!

Problem 18.1.3.

An alternative model allows there to be state-level effects:

\[ murder_{i,t} N(\alpha_i + \beta_i \times penalty_{i,t} + \gamma_i \times car_{i,t}, \sigma_i) \]

where we assume that \(\alpha_i N(\bar{\alpha}, \sigma_\alpha)\), \(\beta_i N(\bar{\beta}, \sigma_\beta)\) and \(\gamma_i N(\bar{\gamma}, \sigma_\gamma)\) (we assume fully heterogeneous estimates for \(\sigma\)). Estimate the above model and compare the results with the homogeneous coefficient model.

data_list <- list(K       = cp_data$state_name %>% unique %>% length,
                  N       = nrow(cp_data),
                  murder  = cp_data$murder,
                  penalty = cp_data$law,
                  car     = cp_data$car,
                  state   = cp_data$state)

set.seed = 1

fit_2 <- stan(here::here("STAN", "problem_18_1_linear_regression", "c_p_hyer.stan"), 
              data = data_list, 
              iter = 2000, 
              chains = 4, 
              warmup = 1000)
print(fit_2, c("alpha", "beta_car", "beta_penalty", "sigma", "alpha_top",

             "beta_penalty_top", "sigma_penalty_top", "alpha_average",

Problem extra. (Not in main text but wanted to include)

Another model allows there to be time trends in the data:

\[ murder_{i,t} N(\alpha + \delta_i \times t + \beta \times penalty_{i,t} + \gamma \times car_{i,t}, \sigma) \]

where \(_i N(\bar{\delta}, _\delta)\). Again estimate this model and compare the effect size of the death penalty across the three models.

data_list <- list(K       = cp_data$state_name %>% unique %>% length,
                  N       = nrow(cp_data),
                  murder  = cp_data$murder,
                  penalty = cp_data$law,
                  car     = cp_data$car,
                  state   = cp_data$state,
                  t       = cp_data$year)

  point_est = "mean"
